 from Middle English <i>stake</i> ‘stake’ (Old English <i>staca</i>), denoting either someone who made wooden stakes, or possibly a thin person, one as narrow as a stake. It may also have denoted someone who lived near a boundary post. Compare   Staff  .","variant of   Stack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Staff","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from Middle English <i>staf</i> ‘rod, staff, stave’ (Old English <i>stæf</i>), used as a nickname either for a tall, thin person, someone who made staves, or for anyone who carried a staff of office.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Stav, from Old Norse <i>stafr</i>, see   Stava  ."]},{"name":"Staker","meanings":["topographic name for someone who lived by a stake, from Middle English <i>stake</i> ‘stake’ (Old English <i>staca</i>) + <i>-er</i>. Compare   Stake  .","occupational name for someone who made wooden stakes or who drove them into the ground, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>stake</i> ‘stake’ (Old English <i>staca</i>). Compare   Stake  .","English:"]},{"name":"Stakes","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Stake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Birgitta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Brigitta ."],"variants":[{"name":"Birgit","meanings":["Borrowing of the Irish name <i>Brighid</i> (  see  Bridget   ). This name owes its enormous popularity in Scandinavia, especially in Sweden, to  St Birgitta  (  1304–73 ), patron saint of Sweden. She was a noblewoman who bore her husband eight children. After his death, she founded an order of nuns, the ‘Bridgettines’ or Order of the Most Holy Saviour. She also went to Rome, where she attempted to reform religious life."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":42,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Birgitta Arendsdotter Styke was born in 1394, in Åby, Västmanland, Sweden, her father, Arend Styke, was 24 and her mother, Metta Lillie, was 13. She married Bengt Gotskalksson in 1417. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in 1446, in Sweden, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1394–1446":"1394–1446","–1441":"–1441","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1432–Male":"1432–Surnud","1434–1464":"1434–1464","–1471":"–1471","1370–1417":"1370–1417","1381–1450":"1381–1450","ca 1417":"umbes 1417","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1394":"1394","Abt 1434":"umbes 1434","1471":"1471","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1436":"1436","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","Abt 1432":"umbes 1432","about 1404":"umbes 1404","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1441":"1441","1418":"1418","about 1441":"umbes 1441","1417":"1417","Sweden":"Rootsi","of Uppsala, Sweden":"Uppsala, Rootsi","Åby, Västmanland, Sweden":"Åby, Västmanland, Rootsi"},"fi":{"1394–1446":"1394–1446","–1441":"–1441","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1432–Male":"1432–Kuollut","1434–1464":"1434–1464","–1471":"–1471","1370–1417":"1370–1417","1381–1450":"1381–1450","ca 1417":"noin 1417","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1394":"1394","Abt 1434":"noin 1434","1471":"1471","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1436":"1436","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","Abt 1432":"noin 1432","about 1404":"noin 1404","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1441":"1441","1418":"1418","about 1441":"noin 1441","1417":"1417","Sweden":"Ruotsi","of Uppsala, Sweden":"Uppsala, Ruotsi","Åby, Västmanland, Sweden":"Åby, Västmanland, Ruotsi"},"fr":{"1394–1446":"1394–1446","–1441":"–1441","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1420–Male":"1420–D